06697nam a22008895i 9783110622942DE-B159720220131112047.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||220131t20222022gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2021949832  a97831106229427 a10.1515/97831106229422doi  a(DE-B1597)528552  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 7aLIT0041902bisacsh04aThe Courts of Philip II and Alexander the Great :bMonarchy and Power in Ancient Macedonia /ced. by Frances Pownall, Sulochana R. Asirvatham, Sabine Müller. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2022] 4c©2022  a1 online resource (VIII, 304 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tPreface -- tContents -- tIntroduction -- tI The Transformation of Royal Authority: Personal Relationships at the Macedonian Court -- tPhilip and Alexander and the Nature of Their Personal Kingship -- tStorm Clouds over Three Hellenistic Courts: Observations on the Life and Death of Ptolemy Ceraunus -- tII The Courts of Philip and Alexander in the Eyes of Contemporary Greeks -- tDiplomatic Activity at the Court of Philip II -- tKairos, Mistrust of Tyranny and the Rhetoric of Court in Demosthenes’ Olynthiacs -- tThe Exile of Demochares of Leuconoe Revisited -- tPhilip II, Alexander III, and Members of Their Court in Greek Comedy -- tIII The Influence of Persia and the Ancient Near East on Alexander’s Court -- tBosworth on Alexander and the Iranians Revisited: Alexander’s Marriages to Persian Brides at Susa: A Study of Arrian, Anabasis 7.4.4–8 -- tTwo Conceptions of Court at Persepolis -- tPothos or Propaganda? Alexander’s Longing to Reach the Ocean and Argead Imperial Ideology -- tIV Raising a Prince in the Macedonian Court: Stories of Alexander’s Birth and Education -- tThe Serpent Sire of Alexander the Great: A Palinode -- tEducating Alexander: High Culture in the Argead Court through Ancient Texts -- tV Alexander’s Court in Retrospective -- t“The Best Man Among the Dead:” Alexander son of Ammon in an Alexandrian Inscription -- tAlexander or not? The Problem of Alexander-like Portraits in Roman Art -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aRecent scholarship has recognized that Philip II and Alexander the Great adopted elements of their self-fashioning and court ceremonial from previous empires in the Ancient Near East, but it is generally assumed that the advent of the Macedonian court as a locus of politics and culture occurred only in the post-Alexander landscape of the Hellenistic Successors. This volume of ground-breaking essays by leading scholars on Ancient Macedonia goes beyond existing research questions to assess the profound impact of Philip and Alexander on court culture throughout the ages. The papers in this volume offer a thematic approach, focusing upon key institutional, cultural, social, ideological, and iconographical aspects of the reigns of Philip and Alexander. The authors treat the Macedonian court not only as a historical reality, but also as an object of fascination to contemporary Greeks that ultimately became a topos in later reflections on the lives and careers of Philip and Alexander. This collection of papers provides a paradigm-shifting recognition of the seminal roles of Philip and Alexander in the emergence of a new kind of Macedonian kingship and court culture that was spectacularly successful and transformative.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 4aAlexander III., Makedonien, König. 4aAntike. 4aPhilipp II., Makedonien, König. 7aLITERARY CRITICISM / Ancient & Classical.2bisacsh  aAncient Courts and courtiers.  aAncient Kings and Rulers.  aAncient Macedonia.  aPhilip and Alexander of Macedon.1 aAnson, Edward M., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators